Bollinger Bands (BOLL) creates two bands around a moving average (MA). Each is usually 2 standard deviations away from the MA.\n\nAnalysts may use BOLL to help determine whether an asset is undervalued (closer to the lower band) or overvalued (closer to the upper band).

Exponential moving average (EMA) shows the average closing price over a time period. Unlike the moving average (MA), it adds more weight to recent price data.\n\nShorter-term analysts may prefer EMA, as it reacts faster to sudden price swings.

Moving average (MA) shows the average closing price over a period of time. It\'s often used to track price trends. The period is defined by a number of intervals. The length of an interval depends on the span of the chart.\n\nAnalysts compare MAs for different time periods to see whether or not they might expect further increases or decreases in the price of a security.

Moving average convergence divergence (MACD) shows the difference between two exponential moving averages (EMAs): one short-term (the \"fast\" EMA), and one long-term (the \"slow\" EMA). This is plotted against a \"signal line\" (usually the 9-day EMA).\n\nAnalysts may become bullish if the MACD crosses above the signal line, and bearish if it crosses below.

Relative strength index (RSI) uses the magnitude of recent changes in price to evaluate whether an asset is overbought or oversold. Our RSI uses Wilder\'s smoothing, which helps filter out price fluctuations to make it easier to spot trends.\n\nAnalysts generally consider an asset overbought if its RSI is above 70, and oversold if its RSI is below 30.

Volume-weighted average price (VWAP) shows the average price over a time period, adjusting for volume. Periods with higher trading volume will impact VWAP more than periods with lower trading volume.\n\nAnalysts use VWAP to help plan entry and exit points. Generally, they believe an asset is undervalued when the price is below VWAP, and overvalued when the price is above VWAP.

#### How is my projection calculated?
The projected value of your portfolio is calculated using a Monte Carlo simulation, which is commonly used to predict a range of potential outcomes. It represents the median and most likely outcome of 10,000 possible scenarios 
The highest and lowest points in the projection range represent the 95th and 5th percentiles of the outcomes, which are unlikely to happen. 
#### What is the projection based on?
The projection is based on your current portfolio value and asset allocation. It uses historical data and assumed future returns for each major asset class in your portfolio. It factors in an annual advisory fee and monthly rebalancing. It doesn't factor in future inflation, taxes, and pending deposits. 
The default segment highlighted on the chart reflects your time horizon for this account. 
#### Disclosures
The results may vary over time and with each use. You should be aware you may gain or lose more than demonstrated in these projections. Future values are hypothetical—they don't reflect nor guarantee actual investment results.
